{
  "id" : "10761732",
  "contents" : "\"John Simpson (artist)\"\nLee was of the opinion that Simpson was \"\"rather a skillful portraitist than an artist and that his portraits are not without power, but lack instinct and penetration.\"\" One of John Burnet, the engraver, is in the National Portrait Gallery. William IV and many notable persons in his day sat to him. Simpson died at Carlisle House, Soho, in 1847. He left two sons, who practised as artists, of whom Charles Simpson died young in 1848, having contributed a few landscapes to the London exhibitions. The other, Philip Simpson, was a student at the Royal Academy, and obtained some success"
} {
