  "id" : "20994396",
  "contents" : "\"Darrius Heyward-Bey\"\nthe Biletnikoff Award watchlist. He led Maryland in receptions, with 51, and receiving yards, with 786. His 63-yard touchdown reception in the 2007 Emerald Bowl against Oregon State stands as the second-longest in Maryland bowl history. At season's end, Heyward-Bey was awarded the team's Most Valuable Offensive Player honor. During his junior season in 2008, he made 42 catches for 609 yards and five touchdowns, and earned an All-ACC honorable mention. On January 7, 2009, Heyward-Bey announced that he would forgo his senior season to enter the NFL Draft. He finished his career at Maryland second in school history in"
} {
  "id" : "4502755",
  "contents" : "\"2009 Maryland Terrapins football team\"\nthat he would forgo his senior year in order to enter the 2009 NFL Draft on January 7, 2009. In just three years, Heyward-Bey had achieved the number-two spot for Maryland career receiving yards (2,089), behind only Jermaine Lewis. It had been widely speculated throughout the 2008 season that the junior would likely leave for the draft, and Rivals.com, \"\"College Football News\"\", \"\"Sports Illustrated\"\", and ESPN projected him as an early entrant and first-round selection. He was ultimately chosen as the seventh overall pick. Mobile quarterback Josh Portis transferred to the Division II school California University of Pennsylvania for his"
